\chapter{Documentation Standards}\label{chapter:Documentation Standards}

\section{Overview}\label{section:DocumentStandardsOverview}

This chapter discusses the documentation standards used in \hopf. The
standards cover program documentation and user documentation for the
project and should be adhered to at all times. Documentation is
generally written in \LaTeX, possibly as part of a \noweb\ source
file. The intent of the standards is to provide common guidelines for
documentation created for \hopf. Section~\ref{section:Document Class}
discusses the \LaTeX\ class used for \hopf\
documentation. Section~\ref{section:Sectioning} discusses the use of
sectioning commands in the \hopf\ literate
program. Section~\ref{section:Bibliography and Citations} presents the
standards used for bibliography entries and
citations. Section~\ref{section:Labels and References} gives the
standards for the in-document labels and
references. Section~\ref{section:Figures and Tables} gives the
standards for figures and tables. Section~\ref{section:Comments}
presents the standards for comments in the
documentation. Section~\ref{section:Index} discusses the use of an
index in \hopf. Finally, sections~\ref{section:Noweb Template} and
\ref{section:User Template} describe the documentation templates for
\hopf\ documentation files.

\section{Document Class}\label{section:Document Class}
The literate program for \hopf\ uses \LaTeX's \emph{book} document
class instead of the \noweb\ default of \emph{article}. The book is
formatted with 11pt font for a two page layout. The user documentation
format is defined by GAP4. 

