\subsection{Chapters}
Chapters are used for major components of \hopf: domains,
major constructions, standards, legal issues, scripts and Makefiles,
etc. Every chapter must contain at least one section entitled
``Overview.''

\subsection{Sections}
Sections are used for subcomponents of an overall major component:
overview, component category, element category, other subdomains,
etc. If a major component has no significant subcomponents --- for
example, a straightforward construction --- content normally reserved
for subsections may be moved up to be sections.

\subsection{Subsections}\label{subsection:Subsections}
Subsections are used for small amounts of functionality: functions,
operations, declarations, etc. Each subsection will generally contain
a specification, an implementation, and a test
subsubsection. Subsections may be sections if the major component
being described has no significant subcomponents.

\subsection{Subsubsections, Paragraphs, and Subparagraphs}
These sectioning commands are left to the discretion of the
writer. The only expection for these commands is described in
Section~\ref{subsection:Subsections}.

\section{Bibliography and Citations}\label{section:Bibliography and Citations}
The bibliography in \hopf\ contains references to the algorithms and
mathematics involved in the project. The rules for constructing a
reference tag are
\begin{itemize}
\item for one author, the tag is the author's capitalized last name,
\item for two authors, the tag is the authors' last names
concatentated in the order in which they appear and capitalized,
\item for three or more authors, the tag is the first author's
capitalized last name with \texttt{EtAl} appended,
\item if reference is made to two or more papers with the same tag
using the preceding rules, the complete year number in which the paper
was published is appended to the tag,
\item if reference is made to two or more papers with the same tag
using the preceding rules, letters are appended to the tag, starting
with lower case letters in alphabetical order, then upper case letters
in alphabetical order.
\end{itemize}

The bibliography is written in BiBTeX and formatted using the SIAM
bibliography style. BiBTeX strings should be used to denote journal and
conference titles in the bibliography.

The following examples show the rules in use.
\begin{verbatim}
@String{JNC = {Journal of Noncommutative Algebra}}

@Article{Struble1998,
  author =       {Craig A. Struble},
  title =        {The \hopf\ Noncommutative Algebra System},
  journal =      JNC,
  year =         1998,
  volume =       1,
  number =       1,
  pages =        {10--17}
}

@Article{StrubleEtAl,
  author =       {Craig A. Struble and Lenwood S. Heath
                  and Gerard Brunick},
  title =        {Computing Drinfel'd's Double},
  journal =      JNC,
  year =         1998,
  volume =       1,
  number =       1,
  pages =        {18--27}
}

@Book{Struble1996a,
  author =       {Craig A. Struble},
  title =        {Junior Mint: A Compiler for Pascal Junior},
  publisher =    {Struble Home Publishing},
  year =         1996
}

@TechReport{Struble1996b,
  author =       {Craig A. Struble},
  title =        {MOOsburg: A Community Network},
  institution =  {Virginia Tech},
  year =         1996
}
\end{verbatim}

\section{Labels and References}\label{section:Labels and References}
Every sectioning command used in the literate program must have an
accompanying label.

\begin{NOTE}
Modify the sectioning commands to do this
automatically?
\end{NOTE}

The label consists of the complete sectioning command
used, followed by a colon, followed by one or two keywords from the
section title. For example, a chapter named ``Path Algebras'' would
have the label \verb,\label{chapter:PathAlgebras},.

Every figure and table must be labeled. The label for a figure
consists of the word ``figure'', followed by a colon, followed by one
or two keywords for the figure. The label for a table consists of the
word ``table'', followed by a colon, followed by one or two keywords
for the table.

\section{Figures and Tables}\label{section:Figures and Tables}
Figures and tables are to float to the top or be on a page of figures
and tables. Every figure and table must contain a descriptive caption
and a label.

\section{Comments}\label{section:Comments}
\LaTeX\ comments must be used to describe macro definitions in the
document source files. The initials of the macro author must be in the
comment. Other comments can be used at the discretion of the author.

\section{Index}\label{section:Index}
Authors are encouraged to make index entries in the \hopf\
documentation. The \LaTeX\ command to use is \verb,\index,. For example,
\begin{verbatim}
\index{Drinfel'd}
\end{verbatim}
creates an index entry for Drinfel'd, assigning the page number on
which the index command appears to the entry. Index entries must
conform to the MakeIndex standards for entry names. MakeIndex supports
creating sub-entries for index entries.

\section{Referencing Program Variables and Files}\label{section:ProgramVariables}
When program variables and files are referenced in the \noweb\
documentation, they are to be surrounded by
\verb,[,\verb,[,\verb,],\verb,],. % Hack to avoid noweb conflict.
This convention is used by \noweb\ to generate links in HTML generated
documentation and to format using a fixed width font in the printed
documentation.

